{
  "The five functions of the skeletal system are:": "",
  "Protection, movement, filtration, secretion, and excretion": "",
  "Support, movement, digestion, respiration, and circulation": "",
  "Support, growth, repair, immunity, and thermoregulation": "",
  "Support, protection, movement, hematopoiesis, and mineral storage": "",
  "The skeletal system serves five main functions: providing structural support for the body, protecting vital organs (brain, heart, lungs), facilitating movement through joint articulations, producing blood cells via hematopoiesis in red bone marrow, and storing minerals like calcium and phosphorus.": "",
  "The sliding filament theory explains how muscles contract by describing:": "",
  "How bones slide past each other at joints": "",
  "How nerve impulses slide along the axon": "",
  "How actin and myosin filaments interact to shorten the sarcomere during muscle contraction": "",
  "How red blood cells slide through capillaries": "",
  "The sliding filament theory describes muscle contraction at the molecular level. Myosin heads bind to actin filaments and pull them toward the center of the sarcomere using energy from ATP hydrolysis, causing the sarcomere to shorten without the individual filaments themselves changing length.": "",
  "An action potential involves which sequence of ion movements?": "",
  "Sodium influx (depolarization) followed by potassium efflux (repolarization)": "",
  "Potassium influx followed by sodium efflux": "",
  "Simultaneous movement of all ions in the same direction": "",
  "Calcium influx followed by chloride efflux": "",
  "During an action potential, voltage-gated sodium channels open first, allowing Na+ to rush into the cell and causing depolarization (the membrane potential becomes more positive). This is followed by the opening of voltage-gated potassium channels, allowing K+ to flow out and causing repolarization back toward the resting potential.": "",
  "Negative feedback in homeostasis means the response:": "",
  "Always results in a harmful outcome for the body": "",
  "Amplifies the original stimulus until a process is complete": "",
  "Has no effect on the original stimulus": "",
  "Opposes the original stimulus to restore a set point": "",
  "Negative feedback is the most common homeostatic mechanism in the body. The response counteracts or opposes the change that triggered it, bringing the variable back toward its set point. For example, when body temperature rises, cooling mechanisms activate to bring it back down.": "",
  "Positive feedback differs from negative feedback because in positive feedback:": "",
  "The response amplifies the original stimulus, driving a process to completion": "",
  "The response always returns the body to its normal set point": "",
  "The response opposes the stimulus to maintain balance": "",
  "The feedback loop has no effect on the original stimulus": "",
  "In positive feedback, the response enhances and amplifies the original stimulus rather than opposing it. This drives processes to rapid completion, such as oxytocin increasing uterine contractions during labor or the LH surge triggering ovulation. Positive feedback loops are less common than negative feedback and require an external event to stop them.": "",
  "The cardiac cycle consists of which phases in sequence?": "",
  "Ventricular systole, atrial systole, then diastole": "",
  "Only systole and diastole with no distinct atrial phase": "",
  "Atrial systole, ventricular systole, then diastole (relaxation and filling)": "",
  "Diastole, then simultaneous atrial and ventricular systole": "",
  "The cardiac cycle represents one complete heartbeat and follows a coordinated sequence: atrial systole (atria contract to complete ventricular filling), ventricular systole (ventricles contract to eject blood into the aorta and pulmonary trunk), and then diastole (the entire heart relaxes and the ventricles fill passively).": "",
  "Gas exchange occurs at two locations in the body:": "",
  "The pleural cavity and the mediastinum": "",
  "The nasal cavity and the pharynx": "",
  "The alveoli (external respiration) and the tissues (internal respiration)": "",
  "The bronchi and the trachea": "",
  "Gas exchange occurs at two sites: external respiration at the alveoli (where O2 diffuses from air into pulmonary capillary blood and CO2 diffuses from blood into the alveolar air) and internal respiration at the tissue level (where O2 diffuses from systemic capillary blood into cells and CO2 diffuses from cells into the blood).": "",
  "The three processes of urine formation in the nephron are:": "",
  "Absorption, digestion, and elimination": "",
  "Diffusion, osmosis, and active transport": "",
  "Filtration, reabsorption, and secretion": "",
  "Concentration, dilution, and excretion": "",
  "Urine formation involves three sequential processes: glomerular filtration (blood plasma is filtered at the glomerulus into Bowman's capsule), tubular reabsorption (useful substances like glucose, amino acids, and water are returned to the blood), and tubular secretion (additional waste products and excess ions are actively transported from blood into the tubular fluid).": "",
  "The SA node is the heart's natural pacemaker and is located in the:": "",
  "Left ventricle wall": "",
  "Left atrium wall": "",
  "Interventricular septum": "",
  "Right atrium wall": "",
  "The sinoatrial (SA) node is located in the posterior wall of the right atrium near the opening of the superior vena cava. It initiates each heartbeat by spontaneously generating electrical impulses at a rate of 60-100 beats per minute, earning it the designation as the heart's natural pacemaker.": "",
  "Antibodies are produced by which type of immune cell?": "",
  "Plasma cells (differentiated B lymphocytes)": "",
  "Natural killer cells": "",
  "Macrophages": "",
  "Cytotoxic T cells": "",
  "Antibodies (immunoglobulins) are produced exclusively by plasma cells, which are the fully differentiated effector form of B lymphocytes. When a B cell encounters its specific antigen and receives helper T cell signals, it proliferates and differentiates into plasma cells that mass-produce and secrete antigen-specific antibodies.": "",
  "What is hematopoiesis?": "",
  "The destruction of old red blood cells in the spleen": "",
  "The production and development of all blood cells from stem cells in the red bone marrow": "",
  "The process of blood clotting at a wound site": "",
  "The transport of oxygen by hemoglobin in red blood cells": "",
  "Hematopoiesis is the process by which all blood cells (red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets) are produced from multipotent hematopoietic stem cells in the red bone marrow. This continuous process replaces the billions of blood cells that are destroyed daily throughout a person's lifetime.": "",
  "What is a sarcomere?": "",
  "The neuromuscular junction where motor neurons connect to muscle fibers": "",
  "The connective tissue sheath surrounding an entire skeletal muscle": "",
  "The basic contractile unit of skeletal muscle, extending from one Z-line to the next and containing organized actin and myosin filaments": "",
  "The sarcoplasmic reticulum that stores calcium in muscle cells": "",
  "A sarcomere is the fundamental contractile unit of striated muscle, bounded by Z-lines (Z-discs) on each end. It contains organized arrays of thick myosin filaments and thin actin filaments whose overlapping interaction produces the force of contraction as described by the sliding filament theory.": "",
  "What does 'depolarization' mean in the context of nerve and muscle cells?": "",
  "The permanent loss of electrical charge across the cell membrane": "",
  "A shift in membrane potential from its resting negative value toward a more positive value, typically caused by sodium ion influx": "",
  "The active pumping of sodium and potassium ions by the Na+/K+ ATPase": "",
  "The restoration of the resting membrane potential after an action potential": "",
  "Depolarization is the phase of an action potential in which the cell membrane potential becomes less negative (more positive) as voltage-gated sodium channels open and Na+ ions rush into the cell. This change from about -70mV toward +30mV is the initial rising phase of the action potential.": "",
  "What is the glomerular filtration rate (GFR)?": "",
  "The amount of blood flowing through the renal arteries per minute": "",
  "The rate at which urine is excreted from the body": "",
  "The rate at which the kidneys reabsorb glucose from the filtrate": "",
  "The volume of blood plasma filtered by the glomeruli of both kidneys per unit of time, and the best overall indicator of kidney function": "",
  "The glomerular filtration rate (GFR) measures the volume of plasma filtered through the glomerular capillaries into Bowman's capsule per minute, normally about 125 mL/min or 180 L/day. It is considered the best overall indicator of kidney function and is used to stage chronic kidney disease.": "",
  "What is hemoglobin?": "",
  "A hormone that stimulates red blood cell production in the bone marrow, secreted by the kidneys in response to low oxygen levels detected by peritubular interstitial cells": "",
  "An iron-containing protein in red blood cells that binds and transports oxygen, with each molecule capable of carrying up to four oxygen molecules": "",
  "A plasma protein involved in blood clotting that is synthesized by the liver and circulates in inactive form until the coagulation cascade converts it to fibrin strands": "",
  "A white blood cell that fights infection by phagocytosing pathogens and presenting antigens to T helper cells, playing a central role in the adaptive immune response": "",
  "Hemoglobin is a metalloprotein found in red blood cells that consists of four subunits, each containing an iron-containing heme group. Each heme group can reversibly bind one oxygen molecule, allowing each hemoglobin molecule to carry up to four O2 molecules from the lungs to the tissues.": "",
  "What does the hypothalamus regulate?": "",
  "Only memory formation and emotional processing": "",
  "Only heart rate and blood pressure": "",
  "Body temperature, thirst, hunger, circadian rhythms, and endocrine function through its control of the pituitary gland": "",
  "Only voluntary skeletal muscle movement": "",
  "The hypothalamus is the master integrator of the nervous and endocrine systems. It regulates body temperature, thirst, hunger, sleep-wake cycles (circadian rhythms), and controls hormone secretion through its connection to the pituitary gland, making it essential for maintaining homeostasis across virtually all body systems.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'antagonistic hormones'?": "",
  "Hormones that are toxic to the body in large amounts": "",
  "Hormones that have opposing effects on the same target variable, allowing precise regulation": "",
  "Hormones that work together to amplify the same effect": "",
  "Hormones produced by the same gland that cancel each other out": "",
  "Antagonistic hormones have opposite effects on the same physiological variable, allowing precise homeostatic control. The classic example is insulin (lowers blood glucose) and glucagon (raises blood glucose), which work in opposition to maintain blood sugar within a narrow normal range.": "",
  "What is the menstrual cycle?": "",
  "A cycle that only involves the ovaries and has no effect on the uterus": "",
  "A one-time event that occurs during puberty": "",
  "A recurring approximately 28-day cycle regulated by FSH, LH, estrogen, and progesterone that prepares the uterus for potential pregnancy": "",
  "A monthly hormone cycle that only affects mood and behavior": "",
  "The menstrual cycle is an approximately 28-day reproductive cycle regulated by the interplay of four key hormones: FSH and LH from the anterior pituitary, and estrogen and progesterone from the ovaries. These hormones coordinate follicular development, ovulation, and endometrial preparation for potential embryo implantation.": "",
  "What does 'tidal volume' mean?": "",
  "The total capacity of the lungs when fully inflated": "",
  "The volume of air remaining in the lungs after maximal exhalation": "",
  "The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after a maximum inhalation": "",
  "The volume of air inhaled or exhaled during a normal, relaxed breath, approximately 500 mL in adults": "",
  "Tidal volume is the volume of air moved into or out of the lungs during a single normal, quiet breath. In adults, tidal volume is approximately 500 mL. It is one of several lung volumes and capacities measured by spirometry and is used to calculate minute ventilation (tidal volume multiplied by respiratory rate).": "",
  "What is the lymphatic system's dual role in the body?": "",
  "Transporting oxygen and regulating body temperature": "",
  "Returning excess interstitial fluid to the blood circulation and providing immune defense through lymph nodes that filter pathogens": "",
  "Producing hormones and regulating blood glucose levels": "",
  "Producing red blood cells and filtering metabolic waste": "",
  "The lymphatic system serves two critical functions: maintaining fluid balance by collecting excess interstitial fluid and returning it to the venous blood supply, and providing immune surveillance through lymph nodes where immune cells monitor lymph for pathogens and mount immune responses when threats are detected.": "",
  "A student is reviewing for the AP exam and encounters a question about a patient whose blood calcium is dangerously low after thyroid surgery. The patient develops muscle twitching and tingling in the fingers. Which concept from the course explains why accidental removal of the parathyroid glands during thyroid surgery leads to these neuromuscular symptoms?": "",
  "The patient is experiencing an allergic reaction to the surgical anesthesia": "",
  "The surgery damaged the vagus nerve causing loss of parasympathetic tone": "",
  "Without parathyroid hormone (PTH), blood calcium drops because there is no stimulus for bone resorption or renal calcium reabsorption, and hypocalcemia increases neuromuscular excitability causing tetany": "",
  "Loss of thyroid hormone production causes metabolic slowdown": "",
  "This scenario connects the endocrine and musculoskeletal systems. PTH from the parathyroid glands is essential for maintaining blood calcium by stimulating bone resorption and renal calcium reabsorption. Without PTH, calcium levels plummet, increasing the excitability of neurons and muscle fibers, causing involuntary muscle contractions (tetany) and paresthesias.": "",
  "A nursing student observes a patient with atrial fibrillation on the cardiac monitor. Instead of regular P waves followed by QRS complexes, the tracing shows irregular fibrillatory waves. The student remembers the cardiac conduction system from class. Why does atrial fibrillation cause an irregular heart rhythm?": "",
  "Multiple chaotic electrical signals from different atrial foci replace the normal coordinated SA node impulse, causing irregular and random transmission to the ventricles through the AV node": "",
  "The Purkinje fibers are generating the electrical impulses instead of the SA node": "",
  "The ventricles are contracting without any electrical stimulus": "",
  "The SA node is firing too rapidly but in a regular pattern": "",
  "In atrial fibrillation, the normal coordinated electrical impulse from the SA node is replaced by hundreds of chaotic electrical signals originating from multiple atrial foci. These disorganized impulses bombard the AV node, which randomly conducts some to the ventricles, resulting in the characteristic 'irregularly irregular' ventricular rhythm.": "",
  "A physical therapy student is working with a patient who has a torn ACL (anterior cruciate ligament). The patient asks why a torn ligament does not heal as quickly as a muscle strain. Using knowledge of tissue types, what is the best explanation?": "",
  "Ligaments are dense connective tissue with limited blood supply compared to highly vascularized muscle tissue, and reduced blood flow means fewer nutrients and repair cells reach the injury site, significantly slowing the healing process": "",
  "Ligaments and muscles heal at exactly the same rate when properly treated because all connective tissues share the same regenerative capacity regardless of their blood supply or cellular composition": "",
  "The ACL is made of bone tissue rather than dense connective tissue, which takes longer to repair because the process of bone remodeling through osteoblast and osteoclast activity is inherently slower": "",
  "Ligaments cannot heal at all because they lack any regenerative capacity, and every ligament tear requires complete surgical replacement with an autograft or allograft tendon": "",
  "Ligaments are composed of dense regular connective tissue with relatively poor blood supply compared to skeletal muscle, which is highly vascularized. Since healing depends on blood delivering oxygen, nutrients, and repair cells to the injury site, the limited vascularity of ligaments results in significantly slower and often incomplete healing.": "",
  "During a lab practical, a student examines a histology slide showing tissue with closely packed cells, no blood vessels, and a basement membrane. The instructor asks the student to identify the tissue type and explain where it would be found. What is the correct identification?": "",
  "Connective tissue, found in tendons and ligaments, characterized by widely scattered cells in an extensive extracellular matrix with abundant collagen fibers and direct blood supply": "",
  "Epithelial tissue, found lining body surfaces and cavities such as the skin, digestive tract, and respiratory tract, characterized by closely packed cells on a basement membrane with no direct blood supply": "",
  "Muscle tissue, found in the heart and skeletal muscles, characterized by elongated contractile cells containing actin and myosin filaments arranged in sarcomeres for force generation": "",
  "Nervous tissue, found in the brain and spinal cord, characterized by neurons that generate and conduct electrical impulses and glial cells that provide structural and metabolic support": "",
  "The three key features described (closely packed cells, avascular, basement membrane) are hallmarks of epithelial tissue. Epithelial tissue lines and covers body surfaces and cavities, receives nutrients by diffusion from underlying connective tissue, and sits on a basement membrane that anchors it to the tissue below.": "",
  "A patient with chronic kidney disease has a GFR of 15 mL/min (normal is approximately 125 mL/min). The doctor explains that the kidneys can no longer adequately filter blood. The patient asks what processes are failing. Which review of nephron function best answers the question?": "",
  "Only filtration is impaired because the glomerular capillaries are damaged, but the tubular epithelial cells remain fully functional and continue normal reabsorption and secretion processes": "",
  "Only reabsorption is impaired because the tubular epithelial cells are damaged, causing the patient to lose excessive nutrients and electrolytes in the urine while filtration and secretion continue normally": "",
  "All three processes are affected: severely reduced filtration of waste products, impaired selective reabsorption of useful substances, and inadequate secretion of toxins and excess ions, leading to accumulation of waste and electrolyte imbalances": "",
  "The kidneys are only failing to produce erythropoietin because the peritubular interstitial cells are damaged, and the glomerular filtration, tubular reabsorption, and secretion processes all remain normal": "",
  "When GFR drops to 15 mL/min, all three nephron processes are severely compromised. Reduced filtration means less waste is removed from the blood, damaged tubules impair selective reabsorption and secretion, and the remaining functional nephrons cannot compensate, leading to uremia, electrolyte imbalances, fluid retention, and metabolic acidosis.": "",
  "An anatomy instructor presents a case of a patient with myasthenia gravis who experiences progressive muscle weakness that worsens throughout the day. The instructor asks students to connect this disease to their knowledge of the neuromuscular junction. What is the underlying pathophysiology?": "",
  "The motor neurons in the spinal cord and brainstem are dying through a process similar to ALS, causing progressive denervation of skeletal muscles and irreversible loss of voluntary motor function": "",
  "The muscle fibers themselves are degenerating due to a genetic defect in the dystrophin protein, causing progressive loss of contractile tissue and replacement with fibrotic scar tissue": "",
  "The sarcoplasmic reticulum cannot release calcium during muscle contraction because the ryanodine receptors are defective, preventing excitation-contraction coupling and producing progressive muscle weakness": "",
  "Autoimmune antibodies attack and destroy acetylcholine (ACh) receptors at the neuromuscular junction, reducing the number of available receptors and impairing nerve-to-muscle signal transmission": "",
  "Myasthenia gravis is an autoimmune disorder in which antibodies target and destroy acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction. With fewer functional receptors, acetylcholine released by motor neurons cannot effectively trigger muscle contraction, causing progressive weakness that worsens with repetitive use as remaining receptors become increasingly depleted.": "",
  "A medical student is reviewing a case where a patient's blood pH dropped to 7.25 after a severe asthma attack. The student must explain why prolonged bronchospasm leads to respiratory acidosis. What is the correct pathophysiological chain?": "",
  "Bronchospasm narrows the airways, reducing ventilation and impairing CO2 exhalation; accumulated CO2 combines with water to form carbonic acid, increasing hydrogen ion concentration and lowering blood pH": "",
  "Bronchospasm increases oxygen delivery, which creates excess acid as a byproduct": "",
  "The asthma medications cause the acidosis, not the bronchospasm itself": "",
  "Bronchospasm causes metabolic acidosis from lactic acid production in the lungs": "",
  "During a severe asthma attack, bronchospasm severely restricts airflow, preventing adequate CO2 exhalation. The retained CO2 dissolves in blood to form carbonic acid (CO2 + H2O -> H2CO3 -> H+ + HCO3-), increasing hydrogen ion concentration and causing respiratory acidosis with a pH below the normal 7.35-7.45 range.": "",
  "A couple struggling with infertility visits a reproductive endocrinologist. Tests show the woman has very low FSH and LH levels. The doctor explains this disrupts the menstrual cycle. How do these hormonal deficiencies prevent pregnancy?": "",
  "Low FSH and LH only affect mood and energy levels through reduced gonadal steroid production, but they have no direct effect on fertility because ovulation occurs independently of gonadotropin levels": "",
  "Without adequate FSH, ovarian follicles cannot develop and produce estrogen; without the LH surge, ovulation cannot occur, meaning no egg is released for fertilization and progesterone production is insufficient to prepare the endometrium for implantation": "",
  "Low FSH and LH paradoxically cause excessive estrogen production from the ovaries through a compensatory feedback mechanism, and it is the estrogen excess rather than the gonadotropin deficiency that prevents pregnancy": "",
  "These hormones only affect male fertility by stimulating spermatogenesis and testosterone production in the testes, and they have no role in female reproduction because ovulation is controlled by different hormones": "",
  "FSH and LH are essential drivers of the menstrual cycle. FSH stimulates follicular development and estrogen production in the ovaries, and the LH surge triggers ovulation. Without these hormones, follicles do not mature, no egg is released, the corpus luteum does not form to produce progesterone, and the endometrium is not properly prepared for implantation.": "",
  "A patient with liver cirrhosis develops severe bleeding from a minor cut that will not stop. Lab results show prolonged prothrombin time (PT) and low levels of clotting factors. A student is asked to connect liver function to the coagulation system. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "The liver synthesizes most clotting factors (including fibrinogen and factors II, VII, IX, and X), so cirrhotic liver damage severely impairs clotting factor production, resulting in coagulopathy and prolonged bleeding": "",
  "The patient is taking blood-thinning medications that were not disclosed": "",
  "Liver disease causes excessive platelet production which paradoxically prevents clotting": "",
  "The liver has no role in blood clotting; the bleeding is from thrombocytopenia alone": "",
  "The liver is the primary site of synthesis for most coagulation factors, including fibrinogen and vitamin K-dependent factors II, VII, IX, and X. When cirrhosis destroys liver tissue, the organ can no longer produce adequate clotting factors, resulting in coagulopathy evidenced by prolonged PT and inability to form stable blood clots at injury sites.": "",
  "An AP exam question describes a patient who takes a diuretic medication for high blood pressure and then develops muscle cramps and an irregular heartbeat. A student must identify the connection between the urinary, muscular, and cardiovascular systems in this scenario. What is the best answer?": "",
  "The diuretic directly damaged the heart muscle and skeletal muscle fibers through a toxic effect on the contractile proteins, causing structural degeneration of myocardial and skeletal muscle cells independent of electrolyte changes": "",
  "Lowering blood pressure with diuretics always causes muscle cramps and cardiac arrhythmias regardless of the electrolyte balance, because the reduction in blood pressure itself directly impairs muscle and cardiac function": "",
  "The diuretic increased renal potassium excretion causing hypokalemia, which disrupts both skeletal muscle contraction (causing cramps) and cardiac muscle electrical activity (causing arrhythmias), because potassium is essential for proper action potential generation in all muscle types": "",
  "The patient is dehydrated from the diuretic, and dehydration alone causes all of these symptoms through reduced blood volume and tissue perfusion, independent of any specific electrolyte imbalance or ion channel dysfunction": "",
  "This scenario demonstrates urinary-muscular-cardiovascular integration. Many diuretics increase renal potassium excretion, causing hypokalemia. Potassium is critical for repolarization during action potentials in both skeletal and cardiac muscle, so deficiency causes skeletal muscle cramps and can lead to dangerous cardiac arrhythmias such as ventricular tachycardia.": ""
}